Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

There are currently extremely limited commercial options available to return to the UK from Georgia.
All Georgian land borders have been closed indefinitely, other than for freight and the return of Georgian citizens. Regular scheduled passenger flights to or from Georgia have now been cancelled for an indefinite period
Flights, including via a third country
The only exception will be flights organised by the Georgian Government in co-ordination with Georgian Airways (Airzena) for the purpose of repatriation of Georgian nationals. Georgian Airways is willing to take departing outward passengers on a commercial basis.
There are currently no direct Tbilisi-London flights scheduled but the following flights from Tbilisi International airport on Georgian Airways have been listed on the official Ministry of Foreign Affairs facebook account:
7 April: Tbilisi –Athens
10 April: Tbilisi-Larnaca
12 April: Tbilisi-Berlin
14 April: Tbilisi-Amsterdam
16 April: Tbilisi-Paris
18 April: Tbilisi-Tel Aviv
21 April: Tbilisi-Rome
24 April: Tbilisi-Barcelona
27 April: Tbilisi-Warsaw
You will need to check whether you will be able to get an onward connection to the UK from any of these destinations.
You should contact Georgian Airways direct to make a booking. Contact details: Phone: +995 322 485 511 or +995 322 111 220. Office address:
12 Shota Rustaveli Avenue,
Tbilisi
You should be aware that the Georgian Airways on-line booking system may not accept bookings until 24 hours before departure.
Although there is no public transport, you can get to Tbilisi airport by private car or taxi as long as the social distancing rules are observed (no more than three people in a single vehicle, including the driver).
If you live in the UK and are currently visiting Georgia, you’re strongly advised to return now by commercial means. Don’t run the risk of getting stranded.
What to do
If you cannot leave Georgia at this time, you should:
Follow the advice of local authorities, including local measures, to help minimise your risk of exposure to coronavirus
Find accommodation that’s suitable for your needs
Keep in regular contact with family and friends at home, so they know you are safe and well
Further information
The British Embassy Tbilisi is issuing regular updates on Facebook and Twitter with the latest information on flight departure options for British Nationals wishing to leave Georgia.
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot depart immediately.
